{
  "title": "Testing Strategies for __future__ Code with pytest in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer outlines strategies for testing __future__ code using the popular testing framework, pytest, within the context of Python 3.12+.",

  "key_points": [
    "Understand that __future__ is a mechanism in Python to support new features that are not yet part of the standard library.",
    "Pytest provides a powerful testing infrastructure for Python, but it does not explicitly support __future__ by default.",
    "To test __future__ code with pytest, you'll need to enable the specific __future__ import in your test files and use custom fixtures or plugins.",
    "Use the `from __future__ import XXX` statement at the beginning of the test file or within a fixture function to activate the desired feature.",
    "To create a custom fixture for testing a specific __future__ feature, follow these steps:",
      {
        "step1": "Define the fixture function using the `@pytest.fixture` decorator",
        "step2": "Inside the fixture function, import the __future__ module and enable the desired feature with `from __future__ import XXX`",
        "step3": "Yield control to the test function as usual"
      }
    "Alternatively, use a pytest plugin like 'pytest-future' for seamless integration of __future__ testing.",
    "Version Notes:",
      {
        "Pytest 7.0.1+": "Introduced support for custom fixtures and plugins to enable testing __future__ code."
      }
    "Caveats:",
      {
        "Custom Fixture Approach": "This method requires writing additional fixture functions for each __future__ feature you want to test.",
        "Pytest-Future Plugin": "While providing seamless integration, the pytest-future plugin may not support all __future__ features or require manual configuration."
      }
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "def test_f_string_example():\n  from __future__ import print_function\n  assert 'Pytest' == print(__name__)\n"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "import pytest\n@pytest.fixture(autouse=True)\ndef enable_f_string():\n  from __future__ import print_function\n\n@pytest.mark.usefixtures('enable_f_string')\ndef test_f_string_example():\n  assert 'Pytest' == print(__name__)"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    {
      "Python": "3.12+",
      "pytest": "7.0.1+"
    },
    {
      "Plugin": "pytest-future",
      "version": "Latest version recommended"
    }
  ]
}
